    "Chris Ryan"
  ],
  "published": "2024-06-21",
  "runtimeMin": 112,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins review Jeff Nichols's 'The Bikeriders,' pull in Chris Ryan to build a 'Dudes Rock' movie canon, then get to Yorgos Lanthimos's 'Kinds of Kindness.' After that, Sean talks to Nichols about the long gap between films.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘The Bikeriders’",
      "note": "Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins, Chris Ryan, with Bobby Wagner",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Bikeriders",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Jeff Nichols's first film since 2016, built from Danny Lyon's 1960s photo book about a Midwest motorcycle club (the Vandals). Jodie Comer narrates as Kathy in a big Midwest accent Nichols says is close to the real recordings; Austin Butler is the pristine, barely-speaking Benny; Tom Hardy plays club founder Johnny with a Cagney-by-way-of-Brando voice. Everyone clocks the Goodfellas debt (freeze-frames, narration, the Karen role, an electric-mud needle drop that inverts the Scorsese cut). Sean and Amanda loved it; Sean thinks it lacks a Goodfellas-sized statement about America, Amanda bought the accent completely. Bobby Wagner (Bob) dissents: an Austin Butler allergy and a setting that felt broad, not specific. Also in it: Michael Shannon, Mike Faist as the Lyon stand-in, Norman Reedus, Boyd Holbrook, Toby Wallace, Damon Herriman as Brucie."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The ‘Dudes Rock’ Movie Canon",
      "note": "Chris Ryan's homework: movies where groups of guys hang out and do cool shit",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Hunt for Red October",
          "year": 1990,
          "note": "Sean's contested entry: dudes rocking in collaboration across the Berlin Wall, though there's no getting-the-gang-together montage."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rio Bravo",
          "year": 1959,
          "note": "Chris's platonic ideal: hanging in a saloon, and a five-minute scene of Wayne, Brennan, Nelson, and Dean Martin just singing."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Wild Bunch",
          "year": 1969,
          "note": "One way to be a dude: a band of bandoleros headed to Mexico to kill and steal."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Great Escape",
          "year": 1963,
          "note": "First-ballot: McQueen throwing a baseball against the wall in solitary is the small gesture that seals it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Magnificent Seven",
          "year": 1960,
          "note": "In the hallowed halls The Bikeriders is paying homage to."
        },
        {
          "title": "Goodfellas",
          "year": 1990,
          "note": "The genius model: you want in even as it destroys them. Sean forgot he'd put it on his own list."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Sting",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "The dude gesture can be as small as touching your nose."
        },
        {
          "title": "Husbands",
          "year": 1970,
          "note": "Cassavetes: three men on a messy weekend after a friend's death. Dudes rocking while broken."
        },
        {
          "title": "Kicking and Screaming",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "Can you intellectually rock? Sean's admitted formative influence as a podcaster."
        },
        {
          "title": "California Split",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "Altman's two-hander of gambling and melancholy, Segal and Gould. A movie Sean identifies with."
        },
        {
          "title": "Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "No women aboard; Bettany on cello, iguanas discovered. Badly needed on The Rewatchables."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Right Stuff",
          "year": 1983,
          "note": "Auto-yes. If Sam Shepard's in it, it's a Dudes Rock movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Top Gun",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "Mules and Ryan are in it, but when the rocking happens (volleyball, the bar sing-along), no women about."
        },
        {
          "title": "Great Balls of Fire!",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "The Dennis Quaid Jerry Lee Lewis picture, cued off Top Gun's Jerry Lee singalong."
        },
        {
          "title": "Reservoir Dogs",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "In play, though it tips toward men torturing one another."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ronin",
          "year": 1998,
          "note": "A singular samurai-man rocks, but he distrusts his own crew, and Natasha McElhone may have too many lines."
        },
        {
          "title": "Magic Mike",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "They get the gang together, hit transcendent highs, peter apart, and are mostly okay."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Nice Guys",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Late-period entry; a two-hander that still counts."
        },
        {
          "title": "Triple Frontier",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Chris's modern pick."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ford v Ferrari",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Does two make a band? Plenty of dudes on the teams either way."
        },
        {
          "title": "Everybody Wants Some!!",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "The Linklater college-baseball hang, more the mellow strain of rocking."
        },
        {
          "title": "Midnight Run",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "A two-hander dude's rock, right in line with The Nice Guys."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ferrari",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Even a solitary-genius film has a dinner-table scene where many dudes rock."
        },
        {
          "title": "Heat",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "Invoked via the hot-De Niro photo; the crew rocks, hard."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "‘Kinds of Kindness’",
      "note": "Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Kinds of Kindness",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Lanthimos's return to his early, absurdist mode: a 2-hour-45 triptych co-written with Efthimis Filippou, loosely linked by control (work, love, cult). Amanda's annoyed at her own lukewarm response; both agree the first film, 'The Death of RMF,' is strongest, anchored by Jesse Plemons rather than Emma Stone, who gets her one-per-movie breakdance in the third. Cast doing weird stuff: Stone, Willem Dafoe, Plemons, Margaret Qualley, Hong Chau, Joe Alwyn. It's mannered and hard to sell, but the marketing found an angle: Stone dancing in a commercial."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "note": "Sean Fennessey with the writer-director",
      "guest": "Jeff Nichols on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Shotgun Stories",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "His debut, made with David Gordon Green's help; the big-emotional-scale ambition was there from the start."
        },
        {
          "title": "Take Shelter",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "'I already remade Poltergeist — it's called Take Shelter.' Written the same 2008 summer as Mud, after another project collapsed."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mud",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "He turned down a million-dollar Poltergeist remake to make this at DGA scale, as long as McConaughey said yes."
        },
        {
          "title": "Loving",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "The historical drama that read as his most Hollywood-digestible, until The Bikeriders."
        },
        {
          "title": "Midnight Special",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Released the same year as Loving; after it, he felt he needed to 'refill the well.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "A Quiet Place: Day One",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "He wrote a draft of the prequel for John Krasinski, then stepped away when it stopped feeling like his, and it opened against The Bikeriders in June. 'Sickly ironic.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Dunkirk",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "One of his favorite films, and his case for Tom Hardy: a badass in a mask in a cockpit the whole time."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hud",
          "year": 1963,
          "note": "His last great emotional experience watching something: revisited for a list, the longhorn scene brought him to his knees."
        },
        {
          "title": "Past Lives",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "A recent film that moved him: the wistful sense of the other lives you could have lived."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
